<p>
  When you did those problems above, you proved some very important principles
  about pop-up motion!
</p>

<ul>
  <li>
    Pop-up motion is always <strong>symmetric</strong>.
    This means that
    the total time that the object is in the air is twice the time
    that it takes to go all the way up.
  </li>
  <li>
    Pop-up motion is always <strong>symmetric</strong>.
    This means that
    the final velocity, when the object strikes the ground,
    is precisely the negative of the initial velocity.
  </li>
  <li>
    Because, in these problems, an object rises up
    and then falls to exactly the same spot,
    the vertical displacement \( \Delta y \)
    is equal to zero.
  </li>
</ul>

